{{nihongo foot|'''''King's Knight'''''|キングスナイト|Kingusu Naito|group=lower-alpha|lead=yes}} is a [[scrolling shooter]] [[video game]] developed and published by [[Square (video game company)|Square]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System]] and [[MSX]]. The game was released in Japan on September 18, 1986<ref>https://www.famitsu.com/games/t/9050/,</ref> and in North America in 1989.<ref>{{cite web | author=Nintendo staff | title=NES Games | url=https://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/nes_games.pdf | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101221005931/http://www.nintendo.com/consumer/gameslist/manuals/nes_games.pdf | publisher=[[Nintendo]] | archive-date=December 21, 2010 | access-date=September 24, 2011}}</ref> It was later re-released for the [[Wii]]'s [[Virtual Console]] in Japan on November 27, 2007<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_kn/index.html|title=VC キングスナイト|date=November 24, 2007|access-date=March 14, 2023|archive-date=November 24, 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071124091019/http://www.nintendo.co.jp/wii/vc/vc_kn/index.html|url-status=bot: unknown}}</ref> and in North America on March 24, 2008.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://wii.ign.com/objects/142/14222977.html | title=King's Knight [Virtual Console] | accessdate=2008-07-09 | website=IGN | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080928222756/http://wii.ign.com/objects/142/14222977.html | archivedate=September 28, 2008 | df=mdy-all}}</ref> This would be followed by a release on the Virtual Console in Japan on February 4, 2015, for [[3DS]] and July 6, 2016, for [[Wii U]].

The game became Square's first North American release under their [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]] subsidiary [[Square (video game company)|Squaresoft]], and their first release as an independent company. The 1986 release's title screen credits Workss for programming. ''King's Knight'' saw a second release in [[1987 in video gaming|1987]] on the [[PC-8801|NEC PC-8801mkII SR]] and the [[X1 (computer)|Sharp X1]]. These versions of the game were retitled ''King's Knight Special'' and released exclusively in [[Japan]]. It was the first game designed by [[Hironobu Sakaguchi]] for the [[Nintendo Entertainment System|Famicom]].<ref name="Forbes: interview">{{cite web | author=Barder, Ollie | date=June 29, 2017 | title=Hironobu Sakaguchi Talks About His Admiration For 'Dragon Quest' And Upcoming Projects | website=[[Forbes]] | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2017/06/29/hironobu-sakaguchi-talks-about-his-admiration-for-dragon-quest-and-upcoming-projects/#56402e2615b5 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170715162731/https://www.forbes.com/sites/olliebarder/2017/06/29/hironobu-sakaguchi-talks-about-his-admiration-for-dragon-quest-and-upcoming-projects/#58e98a7f1cb4 | archivedate=2017-07-15 | accessdate=29 June 2019}}</ref> [[Nobuo Uematsu]] provided the musical score for ''King's Knight''. It was Uematsu's third work of [[video game music]] composition.<ref name="interviews">{{cite web | author=Square Enix North America Site Staff | year=2005 | title=Uematsu's Music | url=http://www.square-enix-usa.com/uematsu/profile/index.html | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312044802/http://www.square-enix-usa.com/uematsu/profile/index.html | archivedate=2009-03-12
